var documenterSearchIndex = {"docs":
[{"category":"section","location":"references/#References","page":"References","text":"Canonical references for the techniques implemented in Resurgence.jl, plus the broader resurgence and large-order literature that motivates them.","title":"References"},{"category":"section","location":"references/#Background-reading","page":"References","text":"Bender & Orszag, Advanced Mathematical Methods for Scientists and Engineers (Bender and Orszag, 1978). The standard textbook on asymptotic methods, optimal truncation, and Borel summation as applied to physics. Chapter on Padé approximants is the gentlest entry point.\nCostin, Asymptotics and Borel Summability (Costin, 2008). Modern, mathematically rigorous treatment of Borel summation, lateral sums, and the Stokes phenomenon.","title":"Background reading"},{"category":"section","location":"references/#Resummation-techniques","page":"References","text":"Shanks transformation: (Shanks, 1955).\nMeijer-G resummation: Mera, Pedersen & Nikolić, \"Fast Summation of Divergent Series and Resurgent Transseries in Quantum Field Theories from Meijer-G Approximants\" (Mera et al., 2018). The standard reference for the Borel–hypergeometric–Meijer-G pipeline implemented by borel_meijerg.","title":"Resummation techniques"},{"category":"section","location":"references/#Borel-summation-and-resurgence","page":"References","text":"Sokal, \"An improvement of Watson's theorem on Borel summability\" (Sokal, 1980). The standard sufficient conditions for a divergent series to be uniquely Borel summable.\nStokes, \"On the discontinuity of arbitrary constants which appear in divergent developments\" (Stokes, 1864). The original Stokes phenomenon paper.\nÉcalle, Les fonctions résurgentes (Écalle, 1981). The foundation of alien calculus and the mathematical theory of resurgence.","title":"Borel summation and resurgence"},{"category":"section","location":"references/#Large-order-behaviour-and-instantons","page":"References","text":"Bender & Wu, \"Anharmonic Oscillator\" (Bender and Wu, 1969) and \"Anharmonic Oscillator. II. A Study of Perturbation Theory in Large Order\" (Bender and Wu, 1973). The starting point of large-order perturbation theory in physics; the canonical example of factorial divergence with extractable instanton action.\nSuslov, \"Divergent perturbation series\" (Suslov, 2005). Review of large-order behaviour in field theory, with explicit recipes for extracting S, β, A from coefficients — directly relevant to stokes_fit.","title":"Large-order behaviour and instantons"},{"category":"section","location":"references/#Bibliography","page":"References","text":"Bender, C. M. and Orszag, S. A. (1978). Advanced Mathematical Methods for Scientists and Engineers (McGraw-Hill, New York). Reprinted by Springer (1999) as                Asymptotic Methods and Perturbation Theory.\n\n\n\nBender, C. M. and Wu, T. T. (1969). Anharmonic Oscillator. Phys. Rev. 184, 1231–1260.\n\n\n\nBender, C. M. and Wu, T. T. (1973). Anharmonic Oscillator. II. A Study of Perturbation Theory in Large Order. Phys. Rev. D 7, 1620–1636.\n\n\n\nCostin, O. (2008). Asymptotics and Borel Summability. Vol. 141 of Monographs and Surveys in Pure and Applied Mathematics (Chapman & Hall / CRC, Boca Raton, FL).\n\n\n\nMera, H.; Pedersen, T. G. and Nikolić, B. K. (2018). Fast Summation of Divergent Series and Resurgent Transseries              in Quantum Field Theories from Meijer-G Approximants. Phys. Rev. D 97, 105027, arXiv:1802.06034 [hep-th].\n\n\n\nShanks, D. (1955). Non-linear Transformations of Divergent and Slowly Convergent Sequences. J. Math. Phys. 34, 1–42.\n\n\n\nSokal, A. D. (1980). An improvement of Watson's theorem on Borel summability. J. Math. Phys. 21, 261–263.\n\n\n\nStokes, G. G. (1864). On the discontinuity of arbitrary constants which appear in divergent developments. Trans. Cambridge Philos. Soc. 10, 105–128.\n\n\n\nSuslov, I. M. (2005). Divergent perturbation series. J. Exp. Theor. Phys. 100, 1188–1233.\n\n\n\nÉcalle, J. (1981). Les fonctions résurgentes. Vol. 81 of Publications Mathématiques d'Orsay (Université de Paris-Sud, Orsay). Three volumes (1981–1985).\n\n\n\n","title":"Bibliography"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/lateral_sums/#Lateral-and-median-sums","page":"Lateral and median sums","text":"When the Borel transform of a series has a singularity on the positive real axis, the standard Laplace integral\n\nS(x) = int_0^infty e^-tx  B(t)  dt\n\nruns straight through that singularity and is ill-defined. The classical fix is to deform the contour above (L⁺) or below (L⁻) the singularity. That gives two distinct lateral sums, each complex-valued. Their average is the ambiguity-free median sum and their difference exposes the Stokes discontinuity — the imaginary, non-perturbative content the plain perturbation series can't see on its own.","title":"Lateral and median sums"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/lateral_sums/#Driver:-aₖ-k!","page":"Lateral and median sums","text":"The series S(z) = Σ k! zᵏ has Borel transform 1/(1−t), with a pole at t = 1. At z = 1 the median sum recovers the Cauchy principal value Ei(1)/e ≈ 0.6972, and the Stokes discontinuity has magnitude π/e ≈ 1.1557.\n\nusing Resurgence\nusing Printf\n\na = Float64[Float64(factorial(big(k))) for k in 0:24]   # a_k = k!\nnothing # hide","title":"Driver: aₖ = k!"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/lateral_sums/#Median-sum","page":"Lateral and median sums","text":"v_med = borel_pade_median(a; n = 10, m = 10, x = 1)\n@printf(\"median:        %.6f + %.6fim\\n\", real(v_med), imag(v_med))\n\nThe imaginary part should be numerically zero — borel_pade_median averages L⁺ and L⁻, which are complex conjugates of each other for real input.","title":"Median sum"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/lateral_sums/#Stokes-discontinuity","page":"Lateral and median sums","text":"v_disc = borel_pade_discontinuity(a; n = 10, m = 10, x = 1)\n@printf(\"discontinuity: %.6f + %.6fim\\n\", real(v_disc), imag(v_disc))\n\nMagnitude ≈ π/e ≈ 1.1557, real-valued. This is the imaginary jump that encodes the leading instanton contribution in resurgence-style problems.","title":"Stokes discontinuity"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/lateral_sums/#The-two-lateral-sums","page":"Lateral and median sums","text":"v_plus  = borel_pade_lateral(a; n = 10, m = 10, x = 1, side = +1)\nv_minus = borel_pade_lateral(a; n = 10, m = 10, x = 1, side = -1)\n@printf(\"L+ (side = +1): %.6f + %.6fim\\n\", real(v_plus),  imag(v_plus))\n@printf(\"L- (side = -1): %.6f + %.6fim\\n\", real(v_minus), imag(v_minus))\n\nFor real input these are exact complex conjugates of each other.\n\nwarning: Sign convention\nside = +1 shifts the offending Padé poles by +iε (upper half-plane), so the integration contour passes below them — matching the lateral sum traditionally written S_θ⁻ in the resurgence literature.borel_pade_discontinuity is computed as(L_+1 - L_-1) big (2i) = (S_theta^- - S_theta^+) big (2i)which has magnitude equal to the textbook (S_θ⁺ − S_θ⁻)/(2i) but the opposite sign. Negate the return value if you want the textbook convention.","title":"The two lateral sums"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/lateral_sums/#Le-Roy-variants","page":"Lateral and median sums","text":"The same lateral/median/discontinuity trio exists for Borel–Le Roy:\n\nborel_leroy_pade_lateral(a; n, m, b, x, side, ...)\nborel_leroy_pade_median(a;  n, m, b, x, ...)\nborel_leroy_pade_discontinuity(a; n, m, b, x, ...)\n\nUseful when the Le Roy parameter b improves Padé conditioning on the particular series you have in hand.","title":"Le Roy variants"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/lateral_sums/#When-to-reach-for-these","page":"Lateral and median sums","text":"Median sum: the right \"value\" to report when the standard Borel sum doesn't exist. Real-valued for real input series with complex-conjugate singularity pairs or with isolated positive-real-axis singularities.\nDiscontinuity: the numerical face of resurgence — proportional to the leading non-perturbative contribution e^{−S/g} weighted by the Stokes constant. To extract S and β directly from the coefficients, see Stokes/large-order diagnostics.\nLateral sums individually: useful if downstream code expects a particular contour choice rather than the median.","title":"When to reach for these"},{"category":"section","location":"api/truncation/#Optimal-truncation","page":"Truncation","text":"Optimal-truncation/superasymptotic estimates: stop summing at the smallest term, take the partial sum, and bound the remainder by the size of the smallest term. Free in the sense that no extra computation is needed beyond the partial sums you already have.","title":"Optimal truncation"},{"category":"section","location":"api/truncation/#Public-functions","page":"Truncation","text":"","title":"Public functions"},{"category":"method","location":"api/truncation/#Resurgence.hyperasymptotic-Union{Tuple{AbstractVector{T}}, Tuple{T}} where T<:Number","page":"Truncation","text":"hyperasymptotic(a; x = 1, level = 1, action = nothing, β = nothing, A = nothing)\n\nHyperasymptotic resummation of the formal power series Σₖ a[k+1] · xᵏ.\n\nlevel = 0 returns the optimal-truncation partial sum evaluated at x (the superasymptotic sum). level = 1 adds the leading single-instanton correction, lifting the remainder magnitude from e^{-|S|/x} to e^{-2|S|/x} for problems with a single Stokes singularity at instanton action S on the positive real t-axis.\n\nThe large-order asymptotics a[n+1] ~ A · Γ(n+β) / action^{n+β} are taken verbatim if (action, β, A) are provided, or extracted via stokes_fit otherwise. All three must be provided together or none. The level-1 correction is the leading lateral-Borel piece,\n\nR_{N*}(x) ≈ -i π · A · x^{-β} · exp(-action / x),\n\nwhich matches the imaginary part of the side = +1 lateral Borel–Padé sum (see borel_pade_lateral) — equivalent to picking the +iε deformation of the Borel-Laplace contour around the leading instanton singularity. The exported terminant function provides the smoothed-Stokes-multiplier building block for users wanting to refine the crossover further.\n\nThe convention is Re(action) > 0 (positive instanton action with the Stokes line on the positive real t-axis). For Borel-summable problems whose Stokes singularity sits on the negative real axis the level-1 formula is not applicable, and the function throws — pass an explicit positive action only when the singularity is genuinely on the positive real axis.\n\nLevels ≥ 2 require subleading or trans-series data not extracted by this function and currently throw; the caller should drop down to resum_transseries for those.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.hyperasymptotic"},{"category":"method","location":"api/truncation/#Resurgence.optimal_truncation-Union{Tuple{AbstractVector{T}}, Tuple{T}} where T<:Number","page":"Truncation","text":"optimal_truncation(a) -> (Nstar, partial_sum, smallest_term)\n\nSmallest-term (superasymptotic) truncation of an asymptotic series with coefficients a:\n\nNstar is the index k minimising |a[k]|.\npartial_sum is sum(a[1:Nstar]).\nsmallest_term is |a[Nstar]|, the standard textbook estimate of the superasymptotic remainder.\n\nFor a convergent or monotone series the answer is trivial (Nstar = length(a) or Nstar = 1), but the function is still well-defined and returns the obvious result.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.optimal_truncation"},{"category":"method","location":"api/truncation/#Resurgence.superasymptotic_remainder-Union{Tuple{AbstractVector{T}}, Tuple{T}} where T<:Number","page":"Truncation","text":"superasymptotic_remainder(a)\n\nEstimate the remainder of an asymptotic series at its optimal-truncation order: returns |a[Nstar]|, the magnitude of the smallest-magnitude term. This is the textbook superasymptotic error estimate.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.superasymptotic_remainder"},{"category":"method","location":"api/truncation/#Resurgence.terminant-Tuple{Number, Number}","page":"Truncation","text":"terminant(p, σ)\n\nBerry–Howls terminant function\n\nT_p(σ) = exp(iπp) · Γ(p) · Γ(1 − p, σ) / (2πi)\n\nwhere Γ(s, z) is the upper incomplete gamma. The terminant smoothly crosses the Stokes line: for σ ≫ p it decays exponentially to zero, for σ ≪ p it tends to one, and at the optimal-truncation regime σ ≈ p it takes the value ≈ 1/2.\n\nGeneric over real and complex inputs; promotes to a complex floating-point type compatible with the inputs.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.terminant"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/transseries/#Trans-series","page":"Trans-series","text":"A trans-series\n\nF(g) = sum_j e^-S_jg  g^beta_j  sum_k a_jk  g^k\n\nis the natural object of resurgence theory: the perturbative answer (j = 0) sitting alongside instanton sectors (j ≥ 1) that perturbation theory can't see on its own. This page builds one by hand, evaluates it numerically with resum_transseries, and uses the action-additive arithmetic on top.\n\nPrerequisite: Lateral and median sums. The worked example below is the Stokes-completion of the non-Borel-summable driver from that page, so it helps to have seen the lateral/median story once first.","title":"Trans-series"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/transseries/#Driver:-the-all-positive-series-aₖ-k!","page":"Trans-series","text":"using Resurgence\nusing Printf\n\na = ComplexF64[ComplexF64(factorial(big(k))) for k in 0:24]\nnothing # hide\n\nComplexF64 rather than Float64 because we'll combine the perturbative series with a sector carrying an iπ prefactor in a moment — keeping everything in one eltype lets the TransSeries constructor stay type-stable.\n\nThe bare resummations from Lateral and median sums:\n\nv_median  = borel_pade_median(a;  n = 10, m = 10, x = 1)\nv_lateral = borel_pade_lateral(a; n = 10, m = 10, x = 1, side = +1)\n@printf(\"median      %.6f + %.6fi\\n\", real(v_median),  imag(v_median))\n@printf(\"lateral L+  %.6f + %.6fi\\n\", real(v_lateral), imag(v_lateral))\n\nThe lateral sum picks up an imaginary part ≈ -1.1557 = -π/e at g = 1 that the median doesn't have. Resurgence theory says that imaginary piece is an explicit one-instanton sector: action S = 1 (the Borel-plane pole sits at t = 1), exponent β = -1 (from the 1/g in the residue at t = 1/g), and leading coefficient -iπ. The sign of the iπ here is glued to the package's side = +1 convention; using side = -1 would flip both signs together — see the convention note in Lateral and median sums.","title":"Driver: the all-positive series aₖ = k!"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/transseries/#Building-the-trans-series","page":"Trans-series","text":"# 1-instanton sector: e^{-S/g} g^β · (-iπ + 0·g + 0·g² + …).\n# Pad with zeros to keep the same length as the perturbative tail.\na_inst = ComplexF64[-im * π; zeros(24)]\n\nts = TransSeries([\n    Sector(0.0,  0.0, a),       # perturbative sector\n    Sector(1.0, -1.0, a_inst),  # one-instanton sector\n])\nlength(ts.sectors)\n\nTransSeries is just a Vector{Sector{T}}; each Sector(S, β, a) records one term in Σⱼ e^{-Sⱼ/g} g^{βⱼ} (Σₖ aⱼₖ gᵏ). The two sectors above auto-promote to a common element type, so ts::TransSeries{ComplexF64}.","title":"Building the trans-series"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/transseries/#Numerical-evaluation","page":"Trans-series","text":"g = 1.0\nv = resum_transseries(ts, g; method = BorelPadeMedian(10, 10))\n@printf(\"trans-series at g = 1:  %.6f + %.6fi\\n\", real(v), imag(v))\n@printf(\"lateral L+ (for ref):   %.6f + %.6fi\\n\", real(v_lateral), imag(v_lateral))\n@printf(\"difference:             %.2e\\n\", abs(v - v_lateral))\n\nresum_transseries walks the sector list, calls resum(BorelPadeMedian(10, 10; x = g), sec.a) on each perturbative tail (the method's evaluation point is rebound from 1 to g), multiplies by the prefactor e^{-S/g} g^β, and sums. For the perturbative sector that gives the median; for the trivial instanton sector [-iπ, 0, 0, …] it gives -iπ; the prefactor e^{-1/g} g^{-1} at g = 1 is 1/e; total: median - iπ/e ≈ L⁺.\n\nThe (S, β) labels carry the full g-dependence — change g and the prefactor follows along automatically:\n\ng = 0.5\nv_g  = resum_transseries(ts, g; method = BorelPadeMedian(10, 10))\nv_lp = borel_pade_lateral(a; n = 10, m = 10, x = g, side = +1)\n@printf(\"at g = 0.5: trans-series = %.6f + %.6fi\\n\", real(v_g),  imag(v_g))\n@printf(\"            lateral L+   = %.6f + %.6fi\\n\", real(v_lp), imag(v_lp))\n\nThe β = -1 matters here: the imaginary part now scales as -2π·e^{-2} rather than just -π·e^{-2}.","title":"Numerical evaluation"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/transseries/#Action-additive-arithmetic","page":"Trans-series","text":"The interesting algebraic fact: multiplying two trans-series adds their actions.\n\nseed = TransSeries([Sector(1.0, 0.0, [1.0])])   # bare 1-instanton seed\n[(s.S, s.β, s.a) for s in (seed * seed).sectors]\n\nseed * seed produces a single sector at S = 2, β = 0 with Cauchy product [1] ⋆ [1] = [1] as its perturbative tail — the standard two-instanton action. Addition does the dual operation: sectors with the same (S, β) get merged, and their perturbative tails are summed (padded to the longer length).","title":"Action-additive arithmetic"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/transseries/#Dilute-instanton-gas-via-transseries_exp","page":"Trans-series","text":"transseries_exp(seed; order) builds the truncated Taylor series 1 + seed + seed²/2! + ⋯ + seed^order / order!. With a single-instanton sector as the seed, this is exactly the dilute-instanton-gas expansion:\n\ngas = transseries_exp(seed; order = 4)\n[(s.S, s.a) for s in gas.sectors]\n\nThe k-instanton sector has action k · S and Cauchy-product coefficient 1/k! — what you'd get from formally evaluating exp(c · e^{-S/g}) and reading off the multi-instanton coefficients.","title":"Dilute instanton gas via transseries_exp"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/transseries/#Where-this-fits","page":"Trans-series","text":"You have an explicit instanton prediction — from a saddle-point analysis, an e^{-S/g} correction in a textbook, the Stokes constant of an existing series, etc. — and want to add it to a bare perturbative series. Build a two-sector TransSeries and call resum_transseries.\nYou want to study how a non-perturbative correction interacts with the perturbative one across orders in g. Keep both sectors as full series and let the action-additive arithmetic combine them.\nYou're working with a dilute-instanton-gas approximation (e.g., a partition function of the form Σₙ (c·e^{-S/g})ⁿ / n!). transseries_exp is the direct construction.\nYou want to verify a hypothesised trans-series structure numerically. Drop the (S, β, A) tuple from stokes_fit straight into a Sector constructor and check.\n\nAPI reference: TransSeries, Sector, resum_transseries, transseries_exp.","title":"Where this fits"},{"category":"section","location":"api/stokes/#Stokes/large-order-diagnostics","page":"Stokes diagnostics","text":"Read the instanton action S, exponent β, prefactor A, and subleading corrections cⱼ directly off the coefficient ratios aₖ₊₁/aₖ, via Richardson-accelerated tail extrapolation. See Stokes/large-order diagnostics for a worked example.","title":"Stokes/large-order diagnostics"},{"category":"section","location":"api/stokes/#Public-functions","page":"Stokes diagnostics","text":"","title":"Public functions"},{"category":"method","location":"api/stokes/#Resurgence.stokes_action-Union{Tuple{AbstractVector{T}}, Tuple{T}} where T<:Number","page":"Stokes diagnostics","text":"stokes_action(a; depth = nothing, n = nothing)\n\nExtract the instanton action S from the large-order behaviour of the formal-power-series coefficients a. Builds the sequence\n\nrₖ = a[k+2] / (k · a[k+1]),    k = 1, 2, …, length(a) - 2,\n\nwhich converges to 1/S with O(1/k) corrections, and Richardson-extra- polates the tail.\n\ndepth is the number of Richardson levels (default min(5, (length(a) - 2) ÷ 2 - 1)); n is the tail anchor (default: the largest index that admits the chosen depth). For real a and a sign-alternating series the result is negative; for a non-Borel-summable series with positive-real-axis singularity it is positive.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.stokes_action"},{"category":"method","location":"api/stokes/#Resurgence.stokes_constant-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractVector{T}, Number, Number}} where T<:Number","page":"Stokes diagnostics","text":"stokes_constant(a, S, β; depth = nothing, n = nothing)\n\nExtract the prefactor A once S and β are known. Builds\n\nAₖ = a[k+1] · S^{k+β} / Γ(k + β),\n\nwhich tends to A with O(1/k) corrections, and Richardson-extrapolates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.stokes_constant"},{"category":"method","location":"api/stokes/#Resurgence.stokes_exponent-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractVector{T}, Number}} where T<:Number","page":"Stokes diagnostics","text":"stokes_exponent(a, S; depth = nothing, n = nothing)\n\nExtract the exponent β once S is known. Builds\n\nβₖ = S · a[k+2]/a[k+1] − k,\n\nwhich tends to β with O(1/k) corrections, and Richardson-extrapolates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.stokes_exponent"},{"category":"method","location":"api/stokes/#Resurgence.stokes_fit-Union{Tuple{AbstractVector{T}}, Tuple{T}} where T<:Number","page":"Stokes diagnostics","text":"stokes_fit(a; subleading = 0, depth = nothing, n = nothing)\n\nOne-call combined extraction. Returns a NamedTuple (S, β, A, c) where c is a vector of subleading coefficients of length subleading (possibly empty) fit by least squares to the residual\n\na[k+1] · S^{k+β} / (A · Γ(k + β)) − 1  ≈  c₁/k + c₂/k² + … + c_subleading / k^subleading\n\nover a tail window of the available coefficients.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.stokes_fit"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_guide/#Methods-guide","page":"Methods guide","text":"Which method should you use for which problem? Resurgence.jl ships several families that overlap in coverage but disagree on cost and on what information they need from you. This page is a decision tree.","title":"Methods guide"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_guide/#Quick-lookup","page":"Methods guide","text":"Your series looks like… Try first Then maybe\nConvergent but slow shanks/richardson pade for analytic-continuation needs\nFactorially divergent, alternating sign (Borel-summable) borel_pade conformal_borel_pade if you know where the singularity is\nFactorially divergent, all-positive (non-Borel-summable) borel_pade_median borel_pade_lateral + borel_pade_discontinuity\nBorel transform has known branch point at t = -sing conformal_borel_pade borel_leroy_pade with tuned b\nBorel transform has algebraic branch point in x hermite_pade hermite_pade_value with branch selector\nYou suspect closed form/hypergeometric borel_meijerg The Stieltjes tutorial covers degenerate cases\nJust need a quick error bound on a partial sum optimal_truncation superasymptotic_remainder for the tail estimate alone\nWant S, β, A from large-order behaviour stokes_fit stokes_action/stokes_exponent one at a time","title":"Quick lookup"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_guide/#Decision-tree","page":"Methods guide","text":"                ┌──────────────────────────────────────┐\n                │ Does the partial sum settle as you   │\n                │ add terms?                           │\n                └─┬────────────────────────────────┬───┘\n                  │ Yes (convergent)               │ No (divergent)\n                  ▼                                ▼\n             ┌────────┐                     ┌──────────────────────────┐\n             │ shanks │                     │ Are aₖ alternating in    │\n             │ pade   │                     │ sign?                    │\n             └────────┘                     └─┬──────────────────────┬─┘\n                                              │ Yes                  │ No\n                                              ▼                      ▼\n                                       ┌──────────────┐       ┌────────────────────┐\n                                       │ borel_pade   │       │ borel_pade_median  │\n                                       │ borel_leroy  │       │ + _lateral/_disc │\n                                       │ conformal_   │       │ for ambiguity      │\n                                       │   borel_pade │       └────────────────────┘\n                                       └──────────────┘\n\nIf you don't know whether the series is alternating, look at stokes_fit: real S > 0 means the leading Borel singularity is on the negative real axis (alternating-sign/Borel-summable case); real S < 0 puts it on the positive real axis (non-Borel-summable — reach for the lateral/median methods).","title":"Decision tree"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_guide/#Sequence-acceleration:-Shanks-vs.-Richardson","page":"Methods guide","text":"Both shanks and richardson take a coefficient vector and a starting offset n, and both accept iterated depth (apply the transform depth times).\n\nShanks (Aitken-Δ²) (Shanks, 1955) cancels a geometric tail Aρⁿ exactly. Best when the partial sums look like a geometric approach to the limit.\nRichardson (Bender and Orszag, 1978) cancels a polynomial tail c/n + c'/n² + …. Best when the partial sums approach the limit like 1/nᵖ.\n\nIf you don't know which tail you have, try both and pick the one whose output stabilises faster.","title":"Sequence acceleration: Shanks vs. Richardson"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_guide/#Padé-family","page":"Methods guide","text":"Three flavours, increasing in specialty:\n\npade — linear [n/m] Padé. Solves an (n+m+1)×(n+m+1) linear system; falls back to pinv (via GenericLinearAlgebra.jl) for rank-deficient inputs. The default Padé you want.\npade_cf — Padé via the qd algorithm, returning a continued fraction. Cheaper to evaluate at many x values once built, but only works for n == m or n + 1 == m.\nhermite_pade — quadratic/Hermite Padé. Use this when the function you're approximating has a branch point in x rather than a pole — algebraic branch points need quadratic, not linear, denominators.","title":"Padé family"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_guide/#Borel-side-methods","page":"Methods guide","text":"All Borel methods share the same three-step pipeline:\n\nConstruct the Borel (or Borel–Le Roy) transform of the coefficient sequence in t.\nBuild a Padé approximant of the transform to extend it past the radius of convergence in t.\nLaplace-integrate against e^{-t/x} to recover the resummed value at x.\n\nThe variants differ in how they handle the Padé step:\n\nborel_pade — vanilla Padé in t. Works when the Borel transform has a single isolated singularity on the negative real axis.\nborel_leroy_pade — Borel–Le Roy with parameter b: the factorial damping is Γ(k + 1 + b) instead of k!. The b = -1/2 default is a common physics choice; sweeping b by hand often improves convergence on a particular series.\nconformal_borel_pade — first apply a conformal map that pushes the known Borel singularity to the boundary of the unit disk, then Padé. Best when you know sing (or have estimated it via stokes_action). Subsumes borel_pade for benign cases and beats it when the singularity is known.\n\nFor a series whose Borel transform has a singularity on the positive real axis (S < 0), the standard Laplace integral is ill-defined. Use the lateral/median variants:\n\nborel_pade_lateral (side = ±1) — contour-deformed integral.\nborel_pade_median — (L⁺ + L⁻)/2, the ambiguity-free median.\nborel_pade_discontinuity — (L⁺ − L⁻)/(2i), the imaginary Stokes jump.\n\nThe Le Roy variants (borel_leroy_pade_lateral, _median, _discontinuity) parallel these one-for-one.","title":"Borel-side methods"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_guide/#Closed-form:-Meijer-G","page":"Methods guide","text":"borel_meijerg tries to identify the Borel transform with a hypergeometric pFq, which when Laplace-integrated gives a Meijer-G function — the construction is due to Mera, Pedersen & Nikolić (Mera et al., 2018). The implementation collapses the resulting G onto a single HypergeometricFunctions.pFq call via the Slater identity (the doubled b_h = 1 from Borel–Laplace cancels two of the numerator parameters), so no Meijer-G is ever evaluated directly.\n\nThis wins when it works — closed-form-quality answers from a finite series — but the rational fit P(k)/Q(k) it does internally is rank-deficient on degenerate drivers (the unshifted Stieltjes series is one such trap). See the Stieltjes tutorial for details.","title":"Closed-form: Meijer-G"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_guide/#Truncation-diagnostics","page":"Methods guide","text":"optimal_truncation returns (N*, partial_sum, εN): stop summing at the smallest term, take the partial sum, and an estimate of the error. This is \"free\" — it doesn't compute anything beyond the partial sums you already have — and is a useful sanity check on top of any of the resummation methods above.\n\nsuperasymptotic_remainder is the underlying tail-size estimate on its own.","title":"Truncation diagnostics"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_guide/#Stokes-diagnostics","page":"Methods guide","text":"stokes_fit reads S, β, A (and optionally subleading cⱼ) off the coefficient ratios aₖ₊₁/aₖ via Richardson-accelerated tail extrapolation. Single-quantity helpers exist: stokes_action, stokes_exponent, stokes_constant.\n\nUseful when:\n\nYou want to know where the leading Borel singularity is (sing = S) before reaching for conformal_borel_pade.\nYou're studying the resurgent structure of a problem and want to see whether S matches a known instanton action.\nYou want to compare the discontinuity from borel_pade_discontinuity against the analytic prediction 2π · A/Γ(β) · e^{-S/x}.\n\nSee Stokes/large-order diagnostics for a full worked example.","title":"Stokes diagnostics"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_guide/#Unified-API","page":"Methods guide","text":"Every method has a struct counterpart for the resum(::AbstractResummation, a) dispatcher:\n\nresum(BorelPade(10, 10),               a; x = 1)\nresum(BorelLeRoyPade(10, 10; b = -1/2), a; x = 1)\nresum(ConformalBorelPade(10, 10),      a; x = 1, sing = 1)\nresum(MeijerG(3),                       a; x = 1)\n\nUse the per-method functions when the call is one-off; use the structs when you want to pass a method around as a value (sweeping parameters, configuring a benchmark, etc.). The struct layer is intentionally thin; all the math lives in the per-method functions.","title":"Unified API"},{"category":"section","location":"api/series_acceleration/#Sequence-acceleration","page":"Sequence acceleration","text":"Standard sequence-acceleration tools for slowly-convergent (or slowly-divergent) sequences of partial sums.\n\nFor when to reach for these vs. the Borel-side methods, see the Methods guide.","title":"Sequence acceleration"},{"category":"section","location":"api/series_acceleration/#Public-functions","page":"Sequence acceleration","text":"","title":"Public functions"},{"category":"method","location":"api/series_acceleration/#Resurgence.abel-Union{Tuple{AbstractVector{T}}, Tuple{T}} where T<:Number","page":"Sequence acceleration","text":"abel(a; x = 1)\n\nTruncated Abel-style evaluation Σₖ a[k+1] xᵏ via Horner's method. The classical Abel sum is the radial limit x → 1⁻; this function evaluates the finite power series at a user-supplied x (default x = 1, which reduces to the plain partial sum). Useful as a baseline and as a building block when sweeping x towards 1.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.abel"},{"category":"method","location":"api/series_acceleration/#Resurgence.aitken_steffensen-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{Any, T}} where T<:Number","page":"Sequence acceleration","text":"aitken_steffensen(g, x0; tol = eps(real(typeof(x0))) * 100, maxiter = 100)\n\nSteffensen's iteration for a fixed point of g. Each step evaluates g twice, then Aitken-Δ² accelerates:\n\ny = g(x),    z = g(y),\nx_new = x − (y − x)² / (z − 2 y + x).\n\nConverges quadratically when g has a simple attractive fixed point, in contrast to the linear convergence of plain xₖ₊₁ = g(xₖ) iteration. Returns when |y − x| ≤ tol (the iterate has landed on the fixed point) or |x_new − x| ≤ tol. Throws ArgumentError if the Δ² denominator vanishes away from the fixed point (linear iteration with no curvature — e.g. g(x) = x + c), or if maxiter is exhausted.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.aitken_steffensen"},{"category":"method","location":"api/series_acceleration/#Resurgence.cesaro-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractVector{T}, Integer}} where T<:Number","page":"Sequence acceleration","text":"cesaro(a, n; depth = 1)\n\nCesàro mean of the partial sums of a at index n. With depth = d, the arithmetic-mean averaging is iterated d times; depth = 1 is the standard (C, 1) Cesàro sum.\n\na[k] is the k-th term of the series; with partial sums Aⱼ = sum(a[1:j]),\n\nC⁽¹⁾ₙ = (1/n) Σⱼ₌₁ⁿ Aⱼ,    C⁽ᵏ⁺¹⁾ₙ = (1/n) Σⱼ₌₁ⁿ C⁽ᵏ⁾ⱼ.\n\nUseful mainly as a baseline against more aggressive accelerators; recovers the limit of (C, k)-summable sequences with depth = k.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.cesaro"},{"category":"method","location":"api/series_acceleration/#Resurgence.rho_brezinski-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractVector{T}, Integer}} where T<:Number","page":"Sequence acceleration","text":"rho_brezinski(a, n; depth = 1)\n\nApply Brezinski's ρ-algorithm to the partial sums of a and return the entry at even column 2·depth of the ρ-tableau.\n\na[k] is the k-th term of the series; with partial sums Aⱼ = sum(a[1:j]),\n\nρ_{-1}^{(n)} = 0,    ρ_0^{(n)} = Aₙ,\nρ_{k+1}^{(n)} = ρ_{k-1}^{(n+1)} + (k + 1) / (ρ_k^{(n+1)} − ρ_k^{(n)}).\n\nStructurally identical to wynn_eps but with (k + 1) numerator, which makes the tableau converge geometrically on logarithmically convergent sequences Aₙ ≈ A + C/nᵖ with non-integer p — the regime where richardson (designed for integer power-law tails) stalls.\n\nWhen two consecutive column-k entries coincide the recursion would divide by zero; the implementation returns that entry instead of NaN/Inf.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.rho_brezinski"},{"category":"method","location":"api/series_acceleration/#Resurgence.richardson-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractVector{T}, Integer}} where T<:Number","page":"Sequence acceleration","text":"richardson(a, n; depth = 1)\n\nApply Richardson extrapolation to the partial sums of a, evaluated at index n. With depth = d, the transformation is iterated d times, eliminating the leading 1/n, 1/n², …, 1/nᵈ tails of the asymptotic expansion of the partial-sum sequence.\n\na[k] is the k-th term of the series; the partial sum Aₙ = sum(a[1:n]). The single-application formula is\n\nRₙ = (n+1) Aₙ₊₁ − n Aₙ\n\nFor higher depth, the iterative recursion\n\nT⁽ᵏ⁺¹⁾ⱼ = ((j + k + 1) T⁽ᵏ⁾ⱼ₊₁ − j T⁽ᵏ⁾ⱼ) / (k + 1)\n\nis applied with T⁽⁰⁾ⱼ = Aⱼ. The result is T⁽ᵈ⁾ₙ, identical to the Salzer / Bender-Orszag (§8.1.30) closed form but free of its alternating- sign cancellation. Richardson is the standard companion to shanks for monotone, power-law-convergent series.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.richardson"},{"category":"method","location":"api/series_acceleration/#Resurgence.shanks-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractVector{T}, Integer}} where T<:Number","page":"Sequence acceleration","text":"shanks(a, n; depth = 1)\n\nApply the Shanks transformation to the partial sums of a, evaluated at index n. With depth = k, the transformation is iterated k times, which is the standard practice for accelerating slowly convergent or alternating series.\n\na[k] is the k-th term of the series; the partial sum Aₙ = sum(a[1:n]). The single-application formula is\n\nSₙ = Aₙ₊₁ − (Aₙ₊₁ − Aₙ)² / ((Aₙ₊₁ − Aₙ) − (Aₙ − Aₙ₋₁))\n\nFor higher depth, the transformation is applied to the sequence of Shanks values obtained from the previous round.\n\nWhen consecutive partial-sum differences match exactly (the series has effectively converged, or has a constant tail), the Shanks denominator vanishes; the implementation returns the current partial sum in that case rather than NaN/Inf.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.shanks"},{"category":"method","location":"api/series_acceleration/#Resurgence.theta_brezinski-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractVector{T}, Integer}} where T<:Number","page":"Sequence acceleration","text":"theta_brezinski(a, n; depth = 1)\n\nApply Brezinski's θ-algorithm to the partial sums of a and return the entry at even column 2·depth of the θ-tableau.\n\na[k] is the k-th term of the series; with partial sums Aⱼ = sum(a[1:j]), the recursion is\n\nθ_{-1}^{(n)} = 0,    θ_0^{(n)} = Aₙ,\nθ_{2k+1}^{(n)} = θ_{2k-1}^{(n+1)} + 1 / (θ_{2k}^{(n+1)} − θ_{2k}^{(n)}),\nθ_{2k+2}^{(n)} = θ_{2k}^{(n+1)}\n                 + (θ_{2k}^{(n+2)} − θ_{2k}^{(n+1)})\n                   · (θ_{2k+1}^{(n+2)} − θ_{2k+1}^{(n+1)})\n                 / (θ_{2k+1}^{(n+2)} − 2 θ_{2k+1}^{(n+1)} + θ_{2k+1}^{(n)}).\n\nEven columns carry the accelerated estimates; odd columns are auxiliary. The θ-algorithm complements wynn_eps on sequences where the ε-algorithm breaks down (denominator vanishes), at the cost of three new data points per acceleration level — hence the requirement length(a) ≥ n + 3·depth.\n\nWhen a denominator vanishes the implementation returns the previous-column entry at that position instead of NaN/Inf.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.theta_brezinski"},{"category":"method","location":"api/series_acceleration/#Resurgence.wynn_eps-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractVector{T}, Integer}} where T<:Number","page":"Sequence acceleration","text":"wynn_eps(a, n; depth = 1)\n\nApply the Wynn ε-algorithm to the partial sums of a and return the entry at even column 2·depth of the ε-tableau.\n\na[k] is the k-th term of the series; with partial sums Aⱼ = sum(a[1:j]), the recursion is\n\nε^{(n)}_{-1} = 0,    ε^{(n)}_0 = Aₙ,\nε^{(n)}_{k+1} = ε^{(n+1)}_{k-1} + 1 / (ε^{(n+1)}_k − ε^{(n)}_k).\n\nThe even-column entries are the meaningful approximants; the odd columns are auxiliary. Column 2·depth realises the depth-th-order Shanks transform via its determinantal form. At depth = 1 this is one Aitken-Δ² step and matches shanks(a, n; depth = 1) exactly; at higher depth it differs entry-by-entry from iterated shanks (which iterates the Δ² operator) but shares the same limit, and is typically better conditioned.\n\nWhen two consecutive column-k entries coincide (the sequence has effectively converged at that position), the recursion would divide by zero; the implementation returns that entry instead of NaN/Inf.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.wynn_eps"},{"category":"method","location":"api/series_acceleration/#Resurgence.levin-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractVector{T}, Integer}} where T<:Number","page":"Sequence acceleration","text":"levin(a, n; depth = length(a) - n - 1, variant = :u, β = 1)\n\nApply the Levin sequence transformation to the partial sums of a at index n with transform order depth = k and remainder estimate selected by variant. Frequently outperforms shanks and wynn_eps on monotone divergent or asymptotic series — the regime resurgence cares about.\n\na[k] is the k-th term of the series; with partial sums Aⱼ = sum(a[1:j]),\n\nLₖ⁽ⁿ⁾ = Σⱼ (−1)ʲ C(k,j) (n+j+β)^{k−1} Aₙ₊ⱼ / ωₙ₊ⱼ\n      ─────────────────────────────────────────────\n        Σⱼ (−1)ʲ C(k,j) (n+j+β)^{k−1}      / ωₙ₊ⱼ\n\nwith j = 0, …, k. The remainder-estimate weight ωₙ depends on variant:\n\n:t —  ωₙ = aₙ                   (Smith–Ford t-transformation).\n:u —  ωₙ = (n + β) aₙ           (Smith–Ford u-transformation, default).\n:v —  ωₙ = aₙ aₙ₊₁ / (aₙ₊₁ − aₙ) (Smith–Ford v-transformation).\n\nThe default depth consumes all available data and is safe for every variant; the :v variant additionally requires a[n + depth + 1] because ωₙ₊depth reads one term beyond the partial-sum index.\n\nWhen a term's weight is zero (a vanishes locally) that term is dropped from both sums; if every weight is zero the partial sum Aₙ₊depth is returned.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.levin"},{"category":"method","location":"api/series_acceleration/#Resurgence.sidi_s-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractVector{T}, Integer}} where T<:Number","page":"Sequence acceleration","text":"sidi_s(a, n; depth = length(a) - n - 1, variant = :u, β = 1)\n\nApply Sidi's S-transformation (W-algorithm) to the partial sums of a at index n. Algebraically related to levin but computed via a divided-difference recursion that is O(depth) per step instead of the O(depth²) explicit Levin sum, and is well-conditioned for oscillatory sequences.\n\nWith partial sums Aⱼ = sum(a[1:j]), remainder estimates ωₙ chosen by variant (same :u/:t/:v choices as levin), and nodes ψₙ = 1 / (n + β), the recursion is\n\nM_0⁽ⁿ⁾ = Aₙ / ωₙ,                 N_0⁽ⁿ⁾ = 1 / ωₙ,\nM_k⁽ⁿ⁾ = (M_{k−1}⁽ⁿ⁺¹⁾ − M_{k−1}⁽ⁿ⁾) / (ψₙ₊ₖ − ψₙ),\nN_k⁽ⁿ⁾ = (N_{k−1}⁽ⁿ⁺¹⁾ − N_{k−1}⁽ⁿ⁾) / (ψₙ₊ₖ − ψₙ),\n\nand the result is S_depth⁽ⁿ⁾ = M_depth⁽ⁿ⁾ / N_depth⁽ⁿ⁾. The S-choice ψₙ = 1/(n+β) distinguishes the transformation from the more general W-algorithm and gives geometric convergence for series whose partial sums satisfy Aₙ = A + ωₙ · ψ(n) with ψ(n) ∼ Σ cⱼ / nʲ.\n\nlength(a) ≥ n + depth + 1 for :v; length(a) ≥ n + depth otherwise. Returns the partial sum Aₙ₊depth when the denominator vanishes at the last step.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.sidi_s"},{"category":"method","location":"api/series_acceleration/#Resurgence.weniger-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractVector{T}, Integer}} where T<:Number","page":"Sequence acceleration","text":"weniger(a, n; depth = length(a) - n - 1, β = 1)\n\nApply Weniger's δ-transformation to the partial sums of a at index n with transform order depth = k. Often the single best black-box accelerator for factorially divergent series — the textbook driver is the Stieltjes / Euler series Σ (-1)ᵏ k!.\n\na[k] is the k-th term of the series; with partial sums Aⱼ = sum(a[1:j]),\n\nδₖ⁽ⁿ⁾ = Σⱼ (−1)ʲ C(k,j) (β+n+j)_{k−1} · Aₙ₊ⱼ / aₙ₊ⱼ₊₁\n      ─────────────────────────────────────────────────\n        Σⱼ (−1)ʲ C(k,j) (β+n+j)_{k−1} ·          1 / aₙ₊ⱼ₊₁\n\nwith j = 0, …, k and (x)_p = x(x+1)…(x+p−1) the rising factorial. The remainder estimate ωₙ = aₙ₊₁ makes this a Levin-style transform with factorial rather than power weighting; length(a) ≥ n + depth + 1 is required because the j = depth term reads aₙ₊depth₊₁.\n\nThe constant overall factor 1/(β+n+k)_{k−1} cancels between numerator and denominator and is therefore dropped from the implementation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.weniger"},{"category":"method","location":"api/series_acceleration/#Resurgence.chop!-Union{Tuple{AbstractVector{T}}, Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractVector{T}, Real}} where T<:Real","page":"Sequence acceleration","text":"chop!(x, tol = eps(real(eltype(x))) * 100)\n\nZero out entries of x smaller than tol in absolute value. Two methods:\n\nFor real-eltype x, simply zeros |x[i]| < tol.\nFor complex-eltype x, zeros real and imaginary parts independently. The eltype is preserved (no silent demotion to real), keeping the function type-stable.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.chop!"},{"category":"function","location":"api/series_acceleration/#Resurgence.sparsify!","page":"Sequence acceleration","text":"sparsify!(x, ε = eps(real(eltype(x))) * 100)\n\nElement-wise variant of chop! returning the same vector. Kept as a separate name for compatibility with the original code; behaves identically to chop! for real and complex inputs.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.sparsify!"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/stieltjes/#Stieltjes/Euler-series","page":"Stieltjes / Euler series","text":"The Stieltjes/Euler series\n\nS(z) = sum_k ge 0 (-1)^k  k  z^k\n\nis divergent for every nonzero z, but Borel summable to\n\nS(z) = frac1z  e^1z  E_1left(tfrac1zright)\nquadtextfor z  0\n\nAt z = 1 the exact value is e · E₁(1) ≈ 0.5963473623. This page runs every method in the package against that reference value, side by side.","title":"Stieltjes/Euler series"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/stieltjes/#Setup","page":"Stieltjes / Euler series","text":"using Resurgence\nusing Printf\n\nconst STIELTJES_AT_1 = 0.5963473623231940743410784993\n\n# 25 coefficients in Float64. factorial(big(k)) avoids overflow at k = 21.\na = Float64[(-1.0)^k * Float64(factorial(big(k))) for k in 0:24]\nnothing # hide","title":"Setup"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/stieltjes/#Direct-partial-sum-(asymptotic)","page":"Stieltjes / Euler series","text":"partial = sum(a)\n@printf(\"partial sum (all 25 terms): %+.6e   (err %.2e)\\n\",\n        partial, partial - STIELTJES_AT_1)\n\nThe asymptotic series gets worse the more terms you add — Stieltjes is the textbook divergent example.","title":"Direct partial sum (asymptotic)"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/stieltjes/#Optimal-truncation-(superasymptotic)","page":"Stieltjes / Euler series","text":"Nstar, partial_opt, εN = optimal_truncation(a)\n@printf(\"optimal truncation (N* = %d): %+.6e   (err %.2e, est %.2e)\\n\",\n        Nstar, partial_opt, partial_opt - STIELTJES_AT_1, εN)\n\nN* is the index of the smallest term; the superasymptotic estimate of the remainder is εN. Useful as a free lower bound — you usually want a real resummation method on top.","title":"Optimal truncation (superasymptotic)"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/stieltjes/#Borel–Padé","page":"Stieltjes / Euler series","text":"v_borel_pade = borel_pade(a; n = 10, m = 10, x = 1)\n@printf(\"Borel–Padé[10/10]: %+.6e   (err %.2e)\\n\",\n        v_borel_pade, v_borel_pade - STIELTJES_AT_1)\n\nThe standard tool for factorially divergent, alternating series with a single Borel-plane singularity on the negative real axis.","title":"Borel–Padé"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/stieltjes/#Borel–Le-Roy–Padé","page":"Stieltjes / Euler series","text":"v_borel_lr = borel_leroy_pade(a; n = 10, m = 10, x = 1)   # b = -1/2 by default\n@printf(\"Borel–Le Roy–Padé[10/10] (b = -1/2): %+.6e   (err %.2e)\\n\",\n        v_borel_lr, v_borel_lr - STIELTJES_AT_1)\n\nThe Le Roy parameter b is a knob: setting b = -1/2 is a common physics choice that often helps Padé convergence, but the optimal value is problem-dependent. See borel_leroy_pade for the default and keyword arguments.","title":"Borel–Le Roy–Padé"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/stieltjes/#Conformal-Borel–Padé","page":"Stieltjes / Euler series","text":"v_conformal = conformal_borel_pade(a; n = 10, m = 10, x = 1, sing = 1)\n@printf(\"conformal-Borel–Padé[10/10]: %+.6e   (err %.2e)\\n\",\n        v_conformal, v_conformal - STIELTJES_AT_1)\n\nThe conformal map t → w(t) accumulates the singularity at t = -sing to the boundary of the unit disk in w, then Padé works on the well-behaved re-expansion. Best when you know where the leading Borel singularity is.","title":"Conformal Borel–Padé"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/stieltjes/#Same-problem-at-BigFloat-precision","page":"Stieltjes / Euler series","text":"ab = BigFloat[(-1)^k * factorial(big(k)) for k in 0:40]\nvb = borel_pade(ab; n = 20, m = 20, x = BigFloat(1))\nabs(vb - BigFloat(STIELTJES_AT_1))\n\nFloat64 → BigFloat is a one-character change at the input. The pade fast path uses LU; for rank-deficient fits it falls back to pinv via GenericLinearAlgebra.jl.\n\nnote: Pushing the integration tolerance\nquadgk's integration nodes are computed in Float64 by default. To push past ~1e-14 you have to ask:borel_pade(ab; n = 20, m = 20, x = BigFloat(1),\n           rtol = BigFloat(\"1e-30\"), atol = BigFloat(\"1e-30\"))","title":"Same problem at BigFloat precision"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/stieltjes/#Meijer-G","page":"Stieltjes / Euler series","text":"The Stieltjes series itself is a degenerate driver for Meijer-G (its Borel transform 1/(1+t) is degree-1 rational, so the rational fit P(k)/Q(k) the method uses is rank-deficient at every order). The shifted series aₖ = (−1)ᵏ (k+1)! has Borel transform 1/(1+t)² and is the canonical non-degenerate driver. Its Borel sum at x = 1 is 1 − e · E₁(1) ≈ 0.40365.\n\nconst SHIFTED_REF = 1.0 - STIELTJES_AT_1\na_shifted = Float64[(-1.0)^k * Float64(factorial(big(k + 1))) for k in 0:24]\n\nv_meijerg = borel_meijerg(a_shifted; n = 3, x = 1)\n@printf(\"borel_meijerg (n = 3): %+.6e   (err %.2e)\\n\",\n        v_meijerg, v_meijerg - SHIFTED_REF)\n\nborel_meijerg collapses the resulting G-function onto a single HypergeometricFunctions.pFq call via the Slater identity (the doubled b_h = 1 from Borel–Laplace cancels two of the numerator parameters), so no Meijer-G is ever evaluated directly — and there's no Python dependency.","title":"Meijer-G"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/stieltjes/#Side-by-side","page":"Stieltjes / Euler series","text":"Method Result Error vs. reference\nPartial sum (25 terms) diverges grows with k\nOptimal truncation (N* = 6) ~0.5963 ~1e-3\nBorel–Padé[10/10] ~0.5963474 ~1e-7\nBorel–Le Roy–Padé[10/10] ~0.5963474 ~1e-7\nConformal Borel–Padé[10/10] ~0.5963474 ~1e-8\nBigFloat Borel–Padé[20/20] full precision ≲ 1e-30 w/ rtol\n\nThe point isn't that one method \"wins\" — it's that for a benign single-singularity problem like Stieltjes, all the Borel-side methods agree to many digits. The differences show up on harder problems: see Lateral and median sums for non-Borel-summable inputs.","title":"Side by side"},{"category":"section","location":"api/borel/#Borel-transforms-and-conformal-maps","page":"Borel and conformal","text":"Low-level building blocks: the Borel and Borel–Le Roy transforms in t, their finite-difference ratios for diagnostics, and the conformal map used by conformal_borel_pade.","title":"Borel transforms and conformal maps"},{"category":"section","location":"api/borel/#Borel-and-Borel–Le-Roy-transforms","page":"Borel and conformal","text":"","title":"Borel and Borel–Le Roy transforms"},{"category":"section","location":"api/borel/#Conformal-map","page":"Borel and conformal","text":"","title":"Conformal map"},{"category":"method","location":"api/borel/#Resurgence.borel_leroy_transform-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractVector{T}, Real}} where T<:Number","page":"Borel and conformal","text":"borel_leroy_transform(a, b) -> Vector\n\nBorel–Le Roy transform with parameter b:\n\nB[k] = a[k] / Γ(k + 1 + b)\n\nReduces to the ordinary Borel transform when b = 0. The parameter b is promoted to eltype(a) to keep the result type-stable.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.borel_leroy_transform"},{"category":"method","location":"api/borel/#Resurgence.borel_ratios-Union{Tuple{AbstractVector{T}}, Tuple{T}} where T<:Number","page":"Borel and conformal","text":"borel_ratios(b) -> Vector\n\nReturn the consecutive-coefficient ratios b[k+1] / b[k] of a Borel transform (or any sequence). The length of the result is length(b) - 1. Element type is preserved (no silent demotion to Float64).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.borel_ratios"},{"category":"method","location":"api/borel/#Resurgence.borel_transform-Union{Tuple{AbstractVector{T}}, Tuple{T}} where T<:Number","page":"Borel and conformal","text":"borel_transform(a) -> Vector\n\nCompute the Borel transform of the formal power series with coefficients a:\n\nB[k] = a[k] / k!\n\nThe result has the same length and element type as a. Inverse factorials are generated iteratively (f[k+1] = f[k] / k), so this is overflow-free for arbitrary-precision element types and avoids the ad-hoc BigInt conversion needed when calling factorial(::Int) for k > 20.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.borel_transform"},{"category":"method","location":"api/borel/#Resurgence.conformal_map-Tuple{Real}","page":"Borel and conformal","text":"conformal_map(t; a = 1)\n\nForward conformal map w(t) = (√(1 + t/a) - 1) / (√(1 + t/a) + 1). The parameter a > 0 is the (assumed) location of the nearest Borel-plane singularity on the negative real axis at t = -a.\n\nFor real t in the cut region t < -a, the result is complex (the map sends the cut t-plane to the unit disk). Real t ≥ -a returns a real value; complex t is handled directly.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.conformal_map"},{"category":"method","location":"api/borel/#Resurgence.conformal_map_pair-Tuple{Real}","page":"Borel and conformal","text":"conformal_map_pair(t; a = 1)\n\nForward conformal map v(t) = t / (√(t² + a²) + a) for a complex-conjugate Borel-plane singularity pair at t = ±i·a (a > 0). Maps the cut t-plane to the open unit disk in v; the singularities at t = ±i·a map to v = ±i on the unit circle, and t = ±∞ map to v = ±1.\n\nFor real t the result is real (the map is regular on the real axis); for complex t, the principal-branch square root is used.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.conformal_map_pair"},{"category":"method","location":"api/borel/#Resurgence.conformal_reseries-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractVector{T}, Real, Integer}} where T<:Number","page":"Borel and conformal","text":"conformal_reseries(b, a, N) -> Vector\n\nRe-expand the Borel-plane series with coefficients b (constant term first) under the conformal substitution t = 4·a·w / (1 - w)², producing a vector of N + 1 coefficients in the variable w.\n\nInternally this is power-series composition truncated at order N. No intermediate symbolic engine is required.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.conformal_reseries"},{"category":"method","location":"api/borel/#Resurgence.conformal_reseries_pair-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractVector{T}, Real, Integer}} where T<:Number","page":"Borel and conformal","text":"conformal_reseries_pair(b, a, N) -> Vector\n\nRe-expand the Borel-plane series with coefficients b (constant term first) under the singularity-pair conformal substitution t = 2 a v / (1 - v²), producing a vector of N + 1 coefficients in v.\n\nIdentical structure to conformal_reseries; only the polynomial of t(v) truncated to order N differs. Power-series composition, truncated at every step, so the high-order discarded coefficients never materialise.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.conformal_reseries_pair"},{"category":"method","location":"api/borel/#Resurgence.inverse_conformal_map-Tuple{Number}","page":"Borel and conformal","text":"inverse_conformal_map(w; a = 1)\n\nInverse conformal map t(w) = 4·a·w / (1 - w)².\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.inverse_conformal_map"},{"category":"method","location":"api/borel/#Resurgence.inverse_conformal_map_pair-Tuple{Number}","page":"Borel and conformal","text":"inverse_conformal_map_pair(v; a = 1)\n\nInverse conformal map t(v) = 2 a v / (1 - v²) for the singularity-pair map. Analytic on |v| < 1.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.inverse_conformal_map_pair"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/stokes_diagnostics/#Stokes/large-order-diagnostics","page":"Stokes / large-order diagnostics","text":"A divergent perturbative series with leading large-order behaviour\n\na_k+1 sim A cdot fracGamma(k + beta)S^k+beta\n                  cdot left( 1 + fracc_1k + fracc_2k^2 + cdots right)\n\nencodes its instanton action S, exponent β, prefactor A, and subleading corrections cⱼ directly in the coefficient ratios. Resurgence.jl reads them off via Richardson-accelerated tail extrapolation.","title":"Stokes/large-order diagnostics"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/stokes_diagnostics/#Driver:-aₖ-(k1)!","page":"Stokes / large-order diagnostics","text":"This driver has exact (S, β, A) = (1, 2, 1) and is the canonical non-degenerate test case. The plain Stieltjes series aₖ = (−1)ᵏ k! is too degenerate for the underlying rational fit, which is why the shifted variant is preferred here.\n\nusing Resurgence\n\n# 50 BigFloat coefficients gives Richardson plenty of headroom.\na = BigFloat[BigFloat(factorial(big(k + 1))) for k in 0:49]\nnothing # hide","title":"Driver: aₖ = (k+1)!"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/stokes_diagnostics/#All-in-one-fit","page":"Stokes / large-order diagnostics","text":"fit = stokes_fit(a)\n(S = fit.S, β = fit.β, A = fit.A)\n\nReturns a named tuple with S, β, A — and (optionally) the subleading cⱼ if you ask for them.","title":"All-in-one fit"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/stokes_diagnostics/#Subleading-corrections","page":"Stokes / large-order diagnostics","text":"fit2 = stokes_fit(a; subleading = 2)\nfit2.c\n\nOrder-by-order Richardson extrapolation reads off [c₁, c₂] directly. Higher subleading values cost more coefficients (and more precision) for diminishing accuracy returns.","title":"Subleading corrections"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/stokes_diagnostics/#Single-quantity-helpers","page":"Stokes / large-order diagnostics","text":"The underlying functions are also exposed individually. They take what they need from earlier extractions: stokes_exponent needs S, stokes_constant needs both S and β.\n\nS = stokes_action(a)\nβ = stokes_exponent(a, S)\nA = stokes_constant(a, S, β)\n(S, β, A)\n\nUseful when you want the action S alone — for example as the sing argument to conformal_borel_pade — or when you're sweeping a parameter and plotting how S varies.","title":"Single-quantity helpers"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/stokes_diagnostics/#Complex-S-for-PT-symmetric-problems","page":"Stokes / large-order diagnostics","text":"The fit is element-type generic. For problems where the dominant Borel singularity is a complex-conjugate pair (S = ±i|S|), pass a Complex{T} coefficient vector:\n\nac = ComplexF64.(a)\nstokes_fit(ac).S    # complex S\n\nFloat64 and BigFloat real input return real S, β, A; Complex{T} input returns the corresponding complex tuple. No silent promotion.","title":"Complex S for PT-symmetric problems"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/stokes_diagnostics/#How-the-fit-works-(sketch)","page":"Stokes / large-order diagnostics","text":"The recipe (Bender & Wu 1969/1973 (Bender and Wu, 1969), (Bender and Wu, 1973); Suslov 2005 (Suslov, 2005)):\n\nFrom aₖ, form the ratio sequence rₖ = aₖ₊₁/aₖ. To leading order rₖ ≈ k/S, so 1/S is the slope of the line rₖ vs. k at large k.\nThe exponent β shows up as the next-to-leading correction rₖ ≈ k/S + (β − 1)/S + O(1/k) — extract it from S · rₖ − k.\nThe prefactor A is read off from the asymptotic relation aₖ ≈ A · Γ(k + β)/S^{k+β} once S and β are known.\nRichardson extrapolation (with iterated depth) accelerates the convergence of each tail-extracted quantity, which is critical when only 30–60 coefficients are available.\n\nFor the underlying mathematical literature see the References page.","title":"How the fit works (sketch)"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/stokes_diagnostics/#When-this-won't-work","page":"Stokes / large-order diagnostics","text":"Subleading singularities. If the Borel transform has more than one singularity at comparable distance, the leading-order extraction picks up whichever wins; subleading cⱼ get contaminated.\nSign-alternating with sub-leading complex pair. The leading large-order behaviour is real, but the next contribution can be complex — a Complex{T} fit picks this up.\nInsufficient precision. Float64 runs out of digits for Γ(k + β)/S^{k+β} quickly. Use BigFloat whenever you suspect digit starvation.","title":"When this won't work"},{"category":"section","location":"api/meijerg/#Meijer-G-resummation","page":"Meijer-G","text":"Pure-Julia Meijer-G resummation following Mera, Pedersen & Nikolić (Mera et al., 2018): the implementation collapses the G-function onto a single HypergeometricFunctions.pFq call via the Slater identity (the doubled b_h = 1 from Borel–Laplace cancels two of the numerator parameters), so no Meijer-G is ever evaluated directly and there is no Python dependency.\n\nSee the Stieltjes tutorial for a note on degenerate drivers (the unshifted Stieltjes series is one such trap; the shifted aₖ = (−1)ᵏ (k+1)! is the canonical non-degenerate driver).","title":"Meijer-G resummation"},{"category":"section","location":"api/meijerg/#Public-functions","page":"Meijer-G","text":"","title":"Public functions"},{"category":"method","location":"api/meijerg/#Resurgence.borel_meijerg-Union{Tuple{AbstractVector{T}}, Tuple{T}} where T<:Number","page":"Meijer-G","text":"borel_meijerg(a; n, x = 1, pFq_kwargs...)\n\nMeijer-G resummation of the formal power series with coefficients a, evaluated at argument x.\n\nAlgorithm\n\nTake the Borel transform B[k] = a[k] / k!.\nFit the consecutive Borel ratios B[k+1]/B[k] to a rational P(k)/Q(k) using a (2l+1)×(2l+1) linear system, with l = (n-1) ÷ 2 for odd n and l = (n-2) ÷ 2 for even n (the even branch first strips and normalises by a[2]).\nExtract α = -roots(P) and β = -roots(Q). The Borel transform is then identified with _{l+1}F_l(α, 1; β; γt) with γ = leading(P)/leading(Q).\nThe Borel sum is the Laplace integral, which by the Slater identity is\na[1] · _{l+2}F_l(α, 1, 1; β; γx)               (odd n)\na[1] + a[2]·x · _{l+2}F_l(α, 1, 2; β; γx)     (even n)\nevaluated by HypergeometricFunctions.pFq. For divergent arguments (which is the typical case here, since p > q + 1) pFq uses the Weniger sequence transformation internally.\n\nArguments\n\nn: number of Borel-ratio terms used for the rational fit. Must be ≥ 3. Odd n and n+1 use the same number of ratios 2l+1 with l = (n-1)÷2.\nx: evaluation point. Must be nonzero.\npFq_kwargs: forwarded to HypergeometricFunctions.pFq (e.g. for tuning the Weniger transformation).\n\nNo return_error keyword: unlike the quadgk-based methods, pFq does not expose a residual estimate.\n\nRequires length(a) ≥ n + 1.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.borel_meijerg"},{"category":"section","location":"api/transseries/#Trans-series","page":"Trans-series","text":"Resurgence's natural object: Σⱼ e^{−Sⱼ/g} g^{βⱼ} (Σₖ aⱼₖ gᵏ). The j = 0 sector is the perturbative answer that the Borel/Padé/Meijer-G methods produce on their own; the j > 0 sectors carry instanton, multi-instanton, and other exponentially small contributions. TransSeries packages them together as a list of Sector records and supports action-additive arithmetic; resum_transseries evaluates the whole object at a coupling g by dispatching each sector's perturbative tail through the existing resum surface and applying the prefactor e^{−Sⱼ/g} g^{βⱼ}.","title":"Trans-series"},{"category":"type","location":"api/transseries/#Resurgence.Sector","page":"Trans-series","text":"Sector{T}(S, β, a)\n\nA single trans-series sector representing e^{-S/g} g^β · (Σₖ a[k+1] gᵏ).\n\nS is the action / exponent in the exponential prefactor, β the power of g, and a the vector of perturbative coefficients in g with the constant term first. The outer constructor Sector(S, β, a) promotes its three arguments to a common element type.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.Sector"},{"category":"type","location":"api/transseries/#Resurgence.TransSeries","page":"Trans-series","text":"TransSeries{T}\n\nA trans-series stored as a Vector{Sector{T}}. Construct via\n\nTransSeries(a::AbstractVector) — wraps a as the single perturbative sector Sector(0, 0, a).\nTransSeries([Sector(S₁, β₁, a₁), Sector(S₂, β₂, a₂), …]) — explicit list of sectors; mixed element types are promoted.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.TransSeries"},{"category":"method","location":"api/transseries/#Resurgence.resum_transseries-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{TransSeries{T}, Any}} where T<:Number","page":"Trans-series","text":"resum_transseries(ts::TransSeries, g; method::AbstractResummation)\n\nNumerically evaluate ts at coupling g. For each sector (Sⱼ, βⱼ, aⱼ), the perturbative tail aⱼ is resummed via resum(method, aⱼ) with method's evaluation point rebound to g; the result is multiplied by the prefactor e^{-Sⱼ/g} g^{βⱼ} and the contributions are summed.\n\nSequence-accelerator methods (e.g. Shanks, Richardson) have no internal x and are passed through unchanged; the prefactor still uses g as the coupling.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.resum_transseries"},{"category":"method","location":"api/transseries/#Resurgence.transseries_exp-Union{Tuple{TransSeries{T}}, Tuple{T}} where T<:Number","page":"Trans-series","text":"transseries_exp(ts::TransSeries; order = 4) -> TransSeries\n\nTruncated Taylor expansion 1 + ts + ts²/2! + … + ts^order / order!.\n\nUseful for canonical \"exp(small)\" constructions in resurgence: e.g., taking a single-instanton trans-series and exponentiating to obtain the dilute-instanton-gas trans-series, which contains all multi-instanton sectors up to order copies of the seed.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.transseries_exp"},{"category":"section","location":"api/pade/#Padé-approximants","page":"Padé","text":"Linear [n/m] Padé, continued-fraction (qd) Padé, and Hermite/quadratic Padé for algebraic branch points. The pole-handling utilities used by all Borel–Padé variants are also re-exposed here.\n\nFor when to reach for which variant, see the Methods guide.","title":"Padé approximants"},{"category":"section","location":"api/pade/#Linear-Padé","page":"Padé","text":"","title":"Linear Padé"},{"category":"section","location":"api/pade/#Continued-fraction-Padé-(qd-algorithm)","page":"Padé","text":"","title":"Continued-fraction Padé (qd algorithm)"},{"category":"section","location":"api/pade/#Hermite/quadratic-Padé","page":"Padé","text":"","title":"Hermite/quadratic Padé"},{"category":"section","location":"api/pade/#Pole-handling","page":"Padé","text":"","title":"Pole handling"},{"category":"method","location":"api/pade/#Resurgence.pade-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractVector{T}, Integer, Integer}} where T<:Number","page":"Padé","text":"pade(a, n, m) -> (p::Polynomial, q::Polynomial)\n\nReturn the Padé approximant [n/m] of the formal power series with coefficients a (constant term first): a numerator polynomial p of degree n and a denominator polynomial q of degree m such that\n\np(z) / q(z) = a₀ + a₁ z + a₂ z² + … + O(z^{n+m+1})\n\nRequires length(a) ≥ n + m + 1. Argument order is numerator-first to match the [n/m] notation and the keyword convention used by the Borel–Padé family.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.pade"},{"category":"method","location":"api/pade/#Resurgence.pade_value-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractVector{T}, Integer, Integer, Any}} where T<:Number","page":"Padé","text":"pade_value(a, n, m, x)\n\nEvaluate the Padé approximant [n/m] of a at x, i.e. return p(x) / q(x) where (p, q) = pade(a, n, m).\n\nNote: each call rebuilds the approximant from scratch via pade. To sweep over many x for the same series, call (p, q) = pade(a, n, m) once and evaluate p(x) / q(x) directly to avoid repeating the linear solve.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.pade_value"},{"category":"method","location":"api/pade/#Resurgence.pade_cf-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractVector{T}, Integer, Integer}} where T<:Number","page":"Padé","text":"pade_cf(a, n, m) -> (num::Polynomial, den::Polynomial)\n\nContinued-fraction Padé approximant of the formal power series with coefficients a (constant term first), built via the qd (quotient–difference) algorithm and a 3-term polynomial recurrence on the convergents of the resulting Stieltjes-type S-fraction. Returns a numerator polynomial of degree n and a denominator polynomial of degree m such that\n\nnum(z) / den(z) = a₀ + a₁ z + a₂ z² + … + O(z^{n+m+1})\n\nThe qd algorithm naturally produces only the diagonal staircase Padé sequence [k/k] and [k/k+1]; this implementation therefore restricts to n == m or n + 1 == m. For general (n, m) use pade.\n\nSometimes more numerically stable than the LU/pinv path of pade on ill-conditioned moment problems and the natural object for J-fractions and S-fractions in Stieltjes-series theory. Conversely, it has no graceful rank-deficient fallback: division-by-zero anywhere in the qd table raises ArgumentError directing users back to pade.\n\nRequires length(a) ≥ n + m + 1 and a[1], …, a[n+m] non-zero.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.pade_cf"},{"category":"method","location":"api/pade/#Resurgence.pade_cf_value-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractVector{T}, Integer, Integer, Any}} where T<:Number","page":"Padé","text":"pade_cf_value(a, n, m, x)\n\nEvaluate the continued-fraction Padé approximant of a at x directly via a scalar 3-term recurrence on the CF convergents — no Polynomial construction. Subject to the same n == m or n + 1 == m restriction as pade_cf.\n\nEach call rebuilds the qd table from scratch; to sweep over many x for the same series, call (num, den) = pade_cf(a, n, m) once and evaluate num(x) / den(x) directly.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.pade_cf_value"},{"category":"method","location":"api/pade/#Resurgence.hermite_pade-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractVector{T}, Integer, Integer, Integer}} where T<:Number","page":"Padé","text":"hermite_pade(a, n, m, l) -> (P::Polynomial, Q::Polynomial, R::Polynomial)\n\nHermite / quadratic Padé approximant of the formal power series with coefficients a (constant term first): polynomials P, Q, R of degree at most n, m, l such that\n\nP(z) + Q(z) f(z) + R(z) f(z)² = O(z^{n+m+l+2})\n\nnormalised so that q_0 = 1. Captures algebraic (square-root) branch points of the Borel transform that linear Padé cannot represent.\n\nThe denominator-tail / numerator-then-back substitution mirrors the linear case in pade: the (m + l + 1) × (m + l + 1) system for (q_1, …, q_m, r_0, …, r_l) is solved via LU; on LinearAlgebra.SingularException it falls back to pinv (SVD), the same rank-deficient strategy used by pade.\n\nRequires length(a) ≥ n + m + l + 2.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.hermite_pade"},{"category":"method","location":"api/pade/#Resurgence.hermite_pade_value-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractVector{T}, Integer, Integer, Integer, Any}} where T<:Number","page":"Padé","text":"hermite_pade_value(a, n, m, l, x; branch = nothing)\n\nEvaluate the Hermite / quadratic Padé approximant of a at x by solving R(x)·y² + Q(x)·y + P(x) = 0 and selecting one branch.\n\nBranch selection:\n\nbranch = nothing (default): pick the principal branch that matches f(0) = a[1]. The discriminant at x = 0 is identically (1 + 2·R(0)·a[1])², so the sign is determined analytically without evaluating the other root.\nbranch = +1 or branch = -1: fix the choice of the ±√(disc) term manually. Useful for exploring the conjugate branch (e.g. the lateral Stokes copy of a square-root branch).\n\nFor real-typed a the discriminant Q(x)² − 4·P(x)·R(x) may be negative at points beyond the radius of validity of the approximant; in that case sqrt raises DomainError. Pass a complex x (e.g. complex(x)) to follow the branch into the complex plane.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.hermite_pade_value"},{"category":"section","location":"getting_started/#Getting-started","page":"Getting started","text":"This page walks through installing the package, computing one Borel sum, and pointing you at the next read.","title":"Getting started"},{"category":"section","location":"getting_started/#Install","page":"Getting started","text":"Resurgence.jl is not yet registered in Julia's General registry, so install from GitHub:\n\nusing Pkg\nPkg.add(url = \"https://github.com/schenkse/Resurgence.jl\")\n\nFor development, clone and Pkg.activate:\n\ngit clone https://github.com/schenkse/Resurgence.jl\ncd Resurgence.jl\n\nusing Pkg; Pkg.activate(\".\"); Pkg.instantiate()\nusing Resurgence","title":"Install"},{"category":"section","location":"getting_started/#Requirements","page":"Getting started","text":"Pkg resolves these automatically — you don't need to install them by hand — but here is the full compatibility floor declared in Project.toml:\n\nDependency Minimum version\nJulia 1.10 (LTS)\nGenericLinearAlgebra.jl 0.4\nHypergeometricFunctions.jl 0.3\nLinearAlgebra (stdlib) shipped with Julia ≥ 1\nPolynomialRoots.jl 1\nPolynomials.jl 4\nQuadGK.jl 2\nSpecialFunctions.jl 2\n\nVersions follow Julia's compat semantics — \"0.4\" means ≥ 0.4, < 0.5; \"4\" means ≥ 4, < 5. Test-only extras (Aqua, Test) are not part of the runtime requirements.","title":"Requirements"},{"category":"section","location":"getting_started/#A-first-end-to-end-run","page":"Getting started","text":"The Stieltjes/Euler series S(z) = Σ (−1)ᵏ k! zᵏ is the canonical divergent-but-Borel-summable example. At z = 1 it sums to e · E₁(1) ≈ 0.5963473623. Here's the full pipeline:\n\nusing Resurgence\n\n# 25 coefficients in Float64. Use factorial(big(k)) so we don't overflow at k = 21.\na = Float64[(-1.0)^k * Float64(factorial(big(k))) for k in 0:24]\n\n# Direct partial sum — diverges; the more terms you add, the worse it gets.\nsum(a)\n\n# Optimal truncation: stop at the smallest term. Superasymptotic accuracy.\nNstar, partial_opt, εN = optimal_truncation(a)\n(Nstar, partial_opt, εN)\n\n# Borel–Padé: the standard tool for factorially divergent, alternating series.\nborel_pade(a; n = 10, m = 10, x = 1)\n\nThe reference value is 0.5963473623…, so Borel–Padé already gives ~8 digits from 25 input coefficients.","title":"A first end-to-end run"},{"category":"section","location":"getting_started/#Higher-precision","page":"Getting started","text":"Every method propagates the input element type. Hand it BigFloat and the intermediate Padé fit and Laplace integral are BigFloat too.\n\nusing Resurgence  # hide\n\nab = BigFloat[(-1)^k * factorial(big(k)) for k in 0:40]\nborel_pade(ab; n = 20, m = 20, x = BigFloat(1))\n\nnote: QuadGK and BigFloat\nquadgk evaluates integration nodes in Float64 by default, so even with BigFloat input the quadrature error sits around 1e-14 unless you ask for tighter tolerances. Pass rtol = BigFloat(\"1e-30\") (and a matching atol) explicitly to push further:borel_pade(ab; n = 20, m = 20, x = BigFloat(1),\n           rtol = BigFloat(\"1e-30\"), atol = BigFloat(\"1e-30\"))","title":"Higher precision"},{"category":"section","location":"getting_started/#Functional-vs.-unified-API","page":"Getting started","text":"Both of these compute the same number:\n\nusing Resurgence  # hide\na = Float64[(-1.0)^k * Float64(factorial(big(k))) for k in 0:24]  # hide\n\nborel_pade(a; n = 10, m = 10, x = 1)\n\nresum(BorelPade(10, 10), a)\n\nUse whichever fits your code. Per-method functions are canonical; the resum(::AbstractResummation, …) layer is a thin dispatch shim that lets callers swap methods by changing one struct.","title":"Functional vs. unified API"},{"category":"section","location":"getting_started/#Next-steps","page":"Getting started","text":"Side-by-side comparison of every method on the Stieltjes series: Stieltjes tutorial.\nSeries whose Borel transform has a singularity on the positive real axis (so the standard Laplace integral is ill-defined): Lateral and median sums.\nReading the instanton action S, exponent β, and prefactor A off the large-order behaviour of the coefficients themselves: Stokes/large-order diagnostics.\nPicking a method for your problem: Methods guide.","title":"Next steps"},{"category":"section","location":"api/borel_pade/#Borel–Padé-resummation","page":"Borel–Padé","text":"The full Borel–Padé family: the standard borel_pade, the Le Roy variant borel_leroy_pade, the conformal-map variant conformal_borel_pade, and the lateral/median/discontinuity sums used for non-Borel-summable inputs. See the lateral and median sums tutorial for a worked example of the latter.\n\nquadgk keyword arguments (rtol, atol, order) flow through to the Laplace integration step in every method here.","title":"Borel–Padé resummation"},{"category":"section","location":"api/borel_pade/#Public-functions","page":"Borel–Padé","text":"","title":"Public functions"},{"category":"method","location":"api/borel_pade/#Resurgence.borel_leroy_pade-Union{Tuple{AbstractVector{T}}, Tuple{T}} where T<:Number","page":"Borel–Padé","text":"borel_leroy_pade(a; n, m, b = -1//2, x = 1, regularize_poles = false,\n                 ε = nothing, side = +1, return_error = false, quad_kwargs...)\n\nBorel–Le Roy–Padé resummation:\n\nBorel–Le Roy transform a with parameter b to obtain B[k] = a[k] / Γ(k+1+b).\nReplace B(t) by its Padé approximant [n/m].\nLaplace-transform with the Le Roy weight:\n ∫₀^∞ t^b (Bₚ(x t) / B_q(x t)) e^{-t} dt.\n\nb may be any real number (including non-integer values); the default -1//2 matches the original code. Pole regularization (regularize_poles, ε, side) works as in borel_pade; selecting opposite sides produces the two lateral Le Roy–Borel sums. quad_kwargs are forwarded to QuadGK.quadgk.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.borel_leroy_pade"},{"category":"method","location":"api/borel_pade/#Resurgence.borel_leroy_pade_discontinuity-Tuple{AbstractVector}","page":"Borel–Padé","text":"borel_leroy_pade_discontinuity(a; n, m, b = -1//2, x = 1, ε = nothing, kwargs...)\n\nStokes discontinuity (L⁺ − L⁻) / (2i) of the Borel–Le Roy–Padé sum.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.borel_leroy_pade_discontinuity"},{"category":"method","location":"api/borel_pade/#Resurgence.borel_leroy_pade_lateral-Union{Tuple{AbstractVector{T}}, Tuple{T}} where T<:Number","page":"Borel–Padé","text":"borel_leroy_pade_lateral(a; n, m, b = -1//2, x = 1, side = +1, ε = nothing, kwargs...)\n\nLateral Borel–Le Roy–Padé sum. Same lateral conventions as borel_pade_lateral; the only difference is the Le Roy weight t^b in the Laplace integrand. ε defaults to √eps(real(eltype(a))), large enough to keep the integrand resolvable across the shifted pole.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.borel_leroy_pade_lateral"},{"category":"method","location":"api/borel_pade/#Resurgence.borel_leroy_pade_median-Tuple{AbstractVector}","page":"Borel–Padé","text":"borel_leroy_pade_median(a; n, m, b = -1//2, x = 1, ε = nothing, kwargs...)\n\nMedian Borel–Le Roy–Padé sum (L⁺ + L⁻) / 2.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.borel_leroy_pade_median"},{"category":"method","location":"api/borel_pade/#Resurgence.borel_leroy_pade_odm-Tuple{AbstractVector}","page":"Borel–Padé","text":"borel_leroy_pade_odm(a; n, m, x = 1, b_grid = range(-0.4, 0.4; length = 17),\n                     return_b = false, kwargs...)\n\nOrder-dependent-mapping (ODM) Borel–Le Roy–Padé sum: sweep the Le Roy parameter b over b_grid, locate the stationary point of the resummation result vs. b, and return the value there. Variational selection of b à la Bender–Boettcher: b is treated as a tunable parameter that the result should depend on weakly.\n\nThe \"stationary point\" is the interior grid index that minimises the forward-difference quotient |Δresult / Δb|; ties are broken by |Δ²result / Δb²| (flattest). With return_b = true, returns a (value, b_star) tuple; otherwise just the value.\n\nb_grid must have at least three points so that a meaningful difference quotient can be formed. The default range stays well inside (-1, 0), where the Borel–Le Roy weight is regular and Γ(k+1+b) has no integer poles.\n\nkwargs... are forwarded to borel_leroy_pade (e.g. rtol, atol for the integration).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.borel_leroy_pade_odm"},{"category":"method","location":"api/borel_pade/#Resurgence.borel_pade-Union{Tuple{AbstractVector{T}}, Tuple{T}} where T<:Number","page":"Borel–Padé","text":"borel_pade(a; n, m, x = 1, regularize_poles = false, ε = nothing,\n           side = +1, return_error = false, quad_kwargs...)\n\nBorel–Padé resummation of the formal power series with coefficients a, evaluated at argument x:\n\nBorel-transform a to obtain B[k] = a[k] / k!.\nReplace B(t) by its Padé approximant [n/m] Bₚ(t) / B_q(t).\nLaplace-transform Bₚ(t) / B_q(t) along the positive real axis:\n ∫₀^∞ (Bₚ(x t) / B_q(x t)) e^{-t} dt.\n\nWhen regularize_poles = true, any poles of the Padé denominator on the positive real axis are first shifted by side · iε (default ε = 100·eps(real(T)), default side = +1) to push them off the contour. This branch is only meaningful for x > 0 because the integration runs along positive t; for x ≤ 0 an ArgumentError is raised. Selecting side = +1 or side = −1 produces the two lateral Borel sums; see borel_pade_lateral.\n\nquad_kwargs are forwarded to QuadGK.quadgk (e.g. rtol, atol, order). With return_error = true, returns a (value, abserr) tuple; otherwise just the value.\n\nRequires length(a) ≥ n + m + 1.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.borel_pade"},{"category":"method","location":"api/borel_pade/#Resurgence.borel_pade_discontinuity-Tuple{AbstractVector}","page":"Borel–Padé","text":"borel_pade_discontinuity(a; n, m, x = 1, ε = nothing, kwargs...)\n\nStokes discontinuity (L⁺ − L⁻) / (2i) of the Borel–Padé sum. Encodes the ambiguity of the lateral sums and is proportional to the leading instanton contribution Stokes_constant · e^{−|S|/x}. For real a the result is real.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.borel_pade_discontinuity"},{"category":"method","location":"api/borel_pade/#Resurgence.borel_pade_lateral-Union{Tuple{AbstractVector{T}}, Tuple{T}} where T<:Number","page":"Borel–Padé","text":"borel_pade_lateral(a; n, m, x = 1, side = +1, ε = nothing, kwargs...)\n\nLateral Borel–Padé sum: shorthand for borel_pade(a; n, m, x, regularize_poles = true, side, ε, kwargs...). The positive-real-axis poles of the Padé denominator are pushed off the contour by side · iε, giving one of the two lateral Borel sums. For real a and real x > 0 the result is generally complex.\n\nConvention: side = +1 shifts poles to +iε (upper half-plane), so the real-axis integration contour passes below them — this matches the lateral sum traditionally written S_θ⁻ in the resurgence literature; side = -1 gives S_θ⁺. Requires x > 0.\n\nDefaults ε to √eps(real(eltype(a))). The lateral integrand has a near-singularity of height ∼1/ε at the shifted pole, so the very tight default of borel_pade (100·eps) makes quadgk underflow; √eps keeps both the pole shift small and the integrand resolvable.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.borel_pade_lateral"},{"category":"method","location":"api/borel_pade/#Resurgence.borel_pade_median-Tuple{AbstractVector}","page":"Borel–Padé","text":"borel_pade_median(a; n, m, x = 1, ε = nothing, kwargs...)\n\nMedian Borel–Padé sum (L⁺ + L⁻)/2, the average of the two lateral sums. For real a the result is purely real (up to roundoff and quadgk tolerance); this is the ambiguity-free real-valued resummation of a non-Borel-summable series.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.borel_pade_median"},{"category":"method","location":"api/borel_pade/#Resurgence.conformal_borel_pade-Union{Tuple{AbstractVector{T}}, Tuple{T}} where T<:Number","page":"Borel–Padé","text":"conformal_borel_pade(a; n, m, x = 1, sing = 1, return_error = false, quad_kwargs...)\n\nConformal-Borel–Padé resummation:\n\nBorel-transform a.\nRe-expand the Borel transform under the conformal map t = 4·sing·w / (1-w)² (see conformal_reseries).\nPadé-approximate the conformal series in w.\nMap back via w = (√(1+t/sing) - 1)/(√(1+t/sing) + 1) and Laplace-integrate along the positive real t axis.\n\nsing > 0 is the assumed location of the nearest singularity of the Borel transform on the negative real axis (i.e. the singularity sits at t = -sing).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.conformal_borel_pade"},{"category":"method","location":"api/borel_pade/#Resurgence.conformal_borel_pade_pair-Union{Tuple{AbstractVector{T}}, Tuple{T}} where T<:Number","page":"Borel–Padé","text":"conformal_borel_pade_pair(a; n, m, x = 1, sing = 1, return_error = false, quad_kwargs...)\n\nConformal-Borel–Padé resummation for a complex-conjugate Borel-plane singularity pair at t = ±i·sing:\n\nBorel-transform a.\nRe-expand the Borel transform under the singularity-pair conformal map t = 2·sing·v / (1 - v²) (see conformal_reseries_pair).\nPadé-approximate the conformal series in v.\nMap back via v = (√(t² + sing²) − sing) / t (numerically as v = t / (√(t² + sing²) + sing)) and Laplace-integrate along the positive real t axis.\n\nsing > 0 is the assumed magnitude of the imaginary singularity pair (singularities at t = ±i·sing). PT-symmetric problems and the quartic anharmonic oscillator are typical use cases.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.conformal_borel_pade_pair"},{"category":"section","location":"#Resurgence.jl","page":"Home","text":"Resummation techniques for divergent and asymptotic series, in pure Julia.\n\nThe package targets resurgence and perturbative-physics workflows: take a formal power series with factorially-growing coefficients, recover a Borel-summable result, and read off the large-order data (instanton action, exponent, prefactor) when you need it. Trans-series — sectors of the form e^{−S/g} g^β (Σₖ aₖ gᵏ) with non-perturbative prefactors — are first-class objects with their own arithmetic and per-sector resummation. Every method is generic over the input element type — Float64, BigFloat, Complex{T} — and there are no Python dependencies.","title":"Resurgence.jl"},{"category":"section","location":"#What's-included","page":"Home","text":"Family Methods\nSequence acceleration Shanks (with iterated depth), Richardson\nPadé approximants Linear, continued-fraction (qd), Hermite/quadratic\nBorel side Borel, Borel–Le Roy, Borel–Padé, conformal Borel–Padé\nLateral/median sums Lateral, median, and discontinuity for Borel–Padé and Borel–Le Roy–Padé\nClosed-form Meijer-G via Slater collapse onto pFq\nTruncation Optimal truncation, superasymptotic remainder\nDiagnostics Stokes action, exponent, constant, joint fit\nTrans-series Sector / TransSeries types with action-additive arithmetic, per-sector resummation via resum_transseries\n\nFor deciding which method to use on which series, see the Methods guide.","title":"What's included"},{"category":"section","location":"#Five-line-install-use","page":"Home","text":"using Pkg\nPkg.add(url = \"https://github.com/schenkse/Resurgence.jl\")\n\nusing Resurgence\n\na = Float64[(-1.0)^k * Float64(factorial(big(k))) for k in 0:24]\nborel_pade(a; n = 10, m = 10, x = 1)   # ≈ 0.5963473623\n\nThe series aₖ = (−1)ᵏ k! is divergent for every nonzero z but Borel summable to (1/z) e^{1/z} E₁(1/z). At z = 1 the exact value is e · E₁(1) ≈ 0.5963473623. See Getting started for the full first run.","title":"Five-line install + use"},{"category":"section","location":"#Two-APIs-over-the-same-engine","page":"Home","text":"A functional API:\n\nborel_pade(a; n = 10, m = 10, x = 1)\nborel_leroy_pade(a; n = 10, m = 10, x = 1)\nconformal_borel_pade(a; n = 10, m = 10, x = 1, sing = 1)\n\n…and a unified dispatch API on top:\n\nresum(BorelPade(10, 10), a)\nresum(BorelLeRoyPade(10, 10), a)\nresum(ConformalBorelPade(10, 10; sing = 1), a)\n\nPer-method functions are canonical; the resum(::AbstractResummation, …) layer is a thin dispatcher that lets you swap methods without changing caller code.","title":"Two APIs over the same engine"},{"category":"section","location":"#Where-to-start","page":"Home","text":"New to the package? Read Getting started.\nHave a divergent series and want to know which method fits? Jump to the Methods guide.\nWant worked physics-style examples? See the Stieltjes tutorial, lateral and median sums, Stokes/large-order diagnostics, or trans-series.\nLooking up a specific function? The API pages (sidebar) auto-generate from source docstrings.","title":"Where to start"},{"category":"section","location":"#License-and-citation","page":"Home","text":"Resurgence.jl is released under the MIT license. If it's useful in published work, please cite the repository directly along with the relevant classical references — see the References page.","title":"License and citation"},{"category":"section","location":"api/api/#Unified-resum-API","page":"Unified resum API","text":"A thin dispatch layer on top of the per-method functions: each resummation method gets an AbstractResummation subtype, and resum(method, a; ...) forwards to the canonical implementation. Use this when you want to pass a method around as a value (for parameter sweeps, configurable benchmarks, etc.); use the per-method functions for one-off calls.","title":"Unified resum API"},{"category":"section","location":"api/api/#Public-types-and-functions","page":"Unified resum API","text":"","title":"Public types and functions"},{"category":"type","location":"api/api/#Resurgence.Abel","page":"Unified resum API","text":"Abel(; x = 1)\n\nAbel-summation tag. resum(Abel(; x), a) calls abel(a; x).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.Abel"},{"category":"type","location":"api/api/#Resurgence.AbstractResummation","page":"Unified resum API","text":"AbstractResummation\n\nAbstract supertype for resummation method tags. See concrete subtypes Shanks, Pade, BorelPade, BorelLeRoyPade, and ConformalBorelPade.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.AbstractResummation"},{"category":"type","location":"api/api/#Resurgence.BorelLeRoyPade","page":"Unified resum API","text":"BorelLeRoyPade(n, m; b = -1//2, x = 1, kwargs...)\n\nBorel–Le Roy–Padé tag. resum(BorelLeRoyPade(n, m; b, x, kwargs...), a) calls borel_leroy_pade(a; n, m, b, x, kwargs...).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.BorelLeRoyPade"},{"category":"type","location":"api/api/#Resurgence.BorelLeRoyPadeODM","page":"Unified resum API","text":"BorelLeRoyPadeODM(n, m; x = 1, b_grid = range(-0.4, 0.4; length = 17), kwargs...)\n\nOrder-dependent-mapping Borel–Le Roy–Padé tag. resum(BorelLeRoyPadeODM(n, m; x, b_grid, kwargs...), a) calls borel_leroy_pade_odm(a; n, m, x, b_grid, kwargs...).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.BorelLeRoyPadeODM"},{"category":"type","location":"api/api/#Resurgence.BorelPade","page":"Unified resum API","text":"BorelPade(n, m; x = 1, kwargs...)\n\nBorel–Padé tag. resum(BorelPade(n, m; x, kwargs...), a) calls borel_pade(a; n, m, x, kwargs...).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.BorelPade"},{"category":"type","location":"api/api/#Resurgence.BorelPadeLateral","page":"Unified resum API","text":"BorelPadeLateral(n, m; x = 1, side = +1, kwargs...)\n\nLateral Borel–Padé tag. resum(BorelPadeLateral(n, m; x, side, kwargs...), a) calls borel_pade_lateral(a; n, m, x, side, kwargs...).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.BorelPadeLateral"},{"category":"type","location":"api/api/#Resurgence.BorelPadeMedian","page":"Unified resum API","text":"BorelPadeMedian(n, m; x = 1, kwargs...)\n\nMedian Borel–Padé tag. resum(BorelPadeMedian(n, m; x, kwargs...), a) calls borel_pade_median(a; n, m, x, kwargs...).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.BorelPadeMedian"},{"category":"type","location":"api/api/#Resurgence.BrezinskiRho","page":"Unified resum API","text":"BrezinskiRho(n; depth = 1)\n\nBrezinski ρ-algorithm tag. resum(BrezinskiRho(n; depth), a) calls rho_brezinski(a, n; depth).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.BrezinskiRho"},{"category":"type","location":"api/api/#Resurgence.BrezinskiTheta","page":"Unified resum API","text":"BrezinskiTheta(n; depth = 1)\n\nBrezinski θ-algorithm tag. resum(BrezinskiTheta(n; depth), a) calls theta_brezinski(a, n; depth).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.BrezinskiTheta"},{"category":"type","location":"api/api/#Resurgence.Cesaro","page":"Unified resum API","text":"Cesaro(n; depth = 1)\n\nCesàro-summation tag. resum(Cesaro(n; depth), a) calls cesaro(a, n; depth).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.Cesaro"},{"category":"type","location":"api/api/#Resurgence.ConformalBorelPade","page":"Unified resum API","text":"ConformalBorelPade(n, m; x = 1, sing = 1, kwargs...)\n\nConformal-Borel–Padé tag. resum(ConformalBorelPade(n, m; x, sing, kwargs...), a) calls conformal_borel_pade(a; n, m, x, sing, kwargs...).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.ConformalBorelPade"},{"category":"type","location":"api/api/#Resurgence.ConformalBorelPadePair","page":"Unified resum API","text":"ConformalBorelPadePair(n, m; x = 1, sing = 1, kwargs...)\n\nConformal-Borel–Padé tag for a complex-conjugate Borel singularity pair at t = ±i·sing. resum(ConformalBorelPadePair(n, m; x, sing, kwargs...), a) calls conformal_borel_pade_pair(a; n, m, x, sing, kwargs...).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.ConformalBorelPadePair"},{"category":"type","location":"api/api/#Resurgence.HermitePade","page":"Unified resum API","text":"HermitePade(n, m, l; x = 1, branch = nothing)\n\nHermite/quadratic Padé tag. resum(HermitePade(n, m, l; x, branch), a) calls hermite_pade_value(a, n, m, l, x; branch).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.HermitePade"},{"category":"type","location":"api/api/#Resurgence.Hyperasymptotic","page":"Unified resum API","text":"Hyperasymptotic(; x = 1, level = 1, kwargs...)\n\nHyperasymptotic-truncation tag. resum(Hyperasymptotic(; x, level, kwargs...), a) calls hyperasymptotic(a; x, level, kwargs...). kwargs may include action, β, A to override the defaults derived from stokes_fit.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.Hyperasymptotic"},{"category":"type","location":"api/api/#Resurgence.Levin","page":"Unified resum API","text":"Levin(n; depth = nothing, variant = :u, β = 1)\n\nLevin sequence-transformation tag. resum(Levin(n; depth, variant, β), a) calls levin(a, n; depth, variant, β). With depth = nothing (default), the function-level default length(a) - n - 1 is used at dispatch time.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.Levin"},{"category":"type","location":"api/api/#Resurgence.MeijerG","page":"Unified resum API","text":"MeijerG(n; x = 1, kwargs...)\n\nMeijer-G resummation tag. resum(MeijerG(n; x, kwargs...), a) calls borel_meijerg(a; n, x, kwargs...).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.MeijerG"},{"category":"type","location":"api/api/#Resurgence.Pade","page":"Unified resum API","text":"Pade(n, m; x = 1)\n\nPadé approximant tag. resum(Pade(n, m; x), a) calls pade_value(a, n, m, x). Argument order is numerator-first to match the Borel–Padé family.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.Pade"},{"category":"type","location":"api/api/#Resurgence.PadeCF","page":"Unified resum API","text":"PadeCF(n, m; x = 1)\n\nContinued-fraction Padé tag. resum(PadeCF(n, m; x), a) calls pade_cf_value(a, n, m, x). Restricted to n == m or n + 1 == m.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.PadeCF"},{"category":"type","location":"api/api/#Resurgence.Richardson","page":"Unified resum API","text":"Richardson(n; depth = 1)\n\nRichardson extrapolation tag. resum(Richardson(n), a) calls richardson(a, n; depth).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.Richardson"},{"category":"type","location":"api/api/#Resurgence.Shanks","page":"Unified resum API","text":"Shanks(n; depth = 1)\n\nShanks transformation tag. resum(Shanks(n), a) calls shanks(a, n; depth).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.Shanks"},{"category":"type","location":"api/api/#Resurgence.SidiS","page":"Unified resum API","text":"SidiS(n; depth = nothing, variant = :u, β = 1)\n\nSidi S-transformation tag. resum(SidiS(n; depth, variant, β), a) calls sidi_s(a, n; depth, variant, β). With depth = nothing (default), the function-level default length(a) - n - 1 is used at dispatch time.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.SidiS"},{"category":"type","location":"api/api/#Resurgence.Weniger","page":"Unified resum API","text":"Weniger(n; depth = nothing, β = 1)\n\nWeniger δ-transformation tag. resum(Weniger(n; depth, β), a) calls weniger(a, n; depth, β). With depth = nothing (default), the function- level default length(a) - n - 1 is used at dispatch time.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.Weniger"},{"category":"type","location":"api/api/#Resurgence.WynnEps","page":"Unified resum API","text":"WynnEps(n; depth = 1)\n\nWynn ε-algorithm tag. resum(WynnEps(n; depth), a) calls wynn_eps(a, n; depth).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.WynnEps"},{"category":"method","location":"api/api/#Resurgence.resum-Tuple{Shanks, Any}","page":"Unified resum API","text":"resum(method::AbstractResummation, a)\n\nApply method to the formal power series with coefficients a.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Resurgence.resum"}]
}
